1
00:00:00,041 --> 00:00:05,666
I got to know someone I spoke with through the wall. The
wall has small holes, I could see his face through them

2
00:00:06,166 --> 00:00:12,000
I asked him his name. He said, Ali al-Wudaihi.
They beat him severely and humiliated him

3
00:00:12,041 --> 00:00:16,166
Two of them would carry him and slam him against the wall. I could
hear the sound of him being beaten, until his bones shattered

4
00:00:17,291 --> 00:00:22,916
He was next to me for four days, but I no longer heard his
voice. He was in the room but there was no sound from him

5
00:00:23,958 --> 00:00:30,166
After that I could not reach him. I called out, Ali,
Ali, but he could not hear me and did not respond

6
00:00:30,750 --> 00:00:38,208
Did they transfer him or did he die? I believe he died, because when
I got out and asked about him, they told me they tortured him to death

7
00:00:39,750 --> 00:00:43,250
Interviewer: Were there <i>sukhra</i> [forced labor]
punishments such as cleaning and other tasks?

8
00:00:43,375 --> 00:00:52,416
We were in solitary cells, they never took us out for forced labor at all. We never
went out even a single meter except for interrogation, inside the solitary cell

9
00:00:53,916 --> 00:00:56,583
Interviewer: Did they
insult you during the torture?

10
00:00:56,708 --> 00:01:04,458
I did not hear insults, just beating
and humiliation. No, no one cursed

11
00:01:04,916 --> 00:01:12,375
The ones they tortured the most were those they
accused of being affiliated with the Free Syrian Army

12
00:01:13,333 --> 00:01:18,541
Those had a special status. They
were tortured heavily. Some people died

13
00:01:19,333 --> 00:01:23,291
And suspension on the walls, and harsh
methods. The suspension was here on the walls

14
00:01:23,541 --> 00:01:33,166
The worst torture methods here were for people who had been
with the Free Syrian Army and those involved in smuggling people

15
00:01:34,125 --> 00:01:38,125
Like Hayel al-Ghadban, this
person was tortured severely

16
00:01:38,291 --> 00:01:42,875
They told him, you were a sniper during the Free
Syrian Army, and you fought against ISIS. As an example

17
00:01:43,583 --> 00:01:51,958
Those were the sounds I would hear, and his screaming, I
did not do anything, while he was suspended on the wall

18
00:01:52,500 --> 00:02:02,083
Like Abdullah al-Naji from Jarniya. They arrested him
and told him, you have 13 rifles and you must bring them

19
00:02:02,458 --> 00:02:07,250
He said, I do not have any. He was severely tortured.
They did not let him off easily, they tortured him heavily

20
00:02:08,458 --> 00:02:16,458
Also, four young men who had found
cameras and ammunition in a room

21
00:02:17,541 --> 00:02:23,125
They wanted to sell them, and
it seems someone reported them

22
00:02:26,958 --> 00:02:36,666
That there was ammunition and informed on them. They found them by
chance, arrested them, and humiliated them severely for a long time

23
00:02:37,166 --> 00:02:41,583
Interviewer: What was the dominant sound
in this place that you heard the most?

24
00:02:41,708 --> 00:02:48,333
The sound of torture. Every
day they took two or three in order

25
00:02:49,083 --> 00:02:54,875
These would have a torture session. They would not leave
them until after torture on the hoist, flogging, and beating

26
00:02:54,916 --> 00:03:02,916
And humiliation and heavy electric
shock. Those were the sounds in this place

